Step 8: Verify the Repository was Cloned

Go to the Jenkins workspace.

cd /var/lib/jenkins/workspace

List the projects.

ls -l

Open your project.

cd <project-name>

Example:

cd webapp

Check the files.

ls -l

If you see your project files, Git cloning was successful.

Step 9: Install Apache Maven

Go to the /opt directory.

cd /opt

Download Maven.

sudo wget https://downloads.apache.org/maven/maven-3/3.9.11/binaries/apache-maven-3.9.11-bin.tar.gz

Extract it.

sudo tar -xvzf apache-maven-3.9.11-bin.tar.gz

Rename the folder.

sudo mv apache-maven-3.9.11 maven

Verify.

ls -l

Go inside Maven.

cd /opt/maven

Check the folders.

ls -l

Verify Maven.

./bin/mvn -v
Step 10: Configure Maven Environment Variables

Go to the root user's home directory.

cd ~

Open the profile.

vi ~/.bash_profile

Add the following lines.

export M2_HOME=/opt/maven
export M2=/opt/maven/bin
export JAVA_HOME=/usr/lib/jvm/java-17-amazon-corretto
export PATH=$PATH:$JAVA_HOME/bin:$M2_HOME/bin

Note: Verify the Java path before saving.

Find Java location.

find /usr/lib/jvm -name java

or

readlink -f $(which java)

Save and exit.

Reload the profile.

source ~/.bash_profile

Verify.

echo $PATH

Check Maven.

mvn -v
